content.description: This route has a few huecos and an interesting juggy feature on it. The moss and sand on it is not too bad.
content.protection: Three bolts at the top to build a top-rope anchor on. There is a large boulder that is easy to back the bolts up with.
content.location: This is located on the down hill side of the crag.

content.description: Aptly named for the cratered slopers and pockets, this route ascends the furthest left line on the rock. With an early crux (and fun, mandatory finger-stack) and few extraneous holds, this route is pretty cerebral for the grade.
content.protection: TR, 3 bolt anchor top and slightly right of route (no rap rings)
content.location: There is a path to get to the base of the rock around the right side (from the perspective of someone looking at the rock head on) but the base of this route is on top of a steep slab. Rapping to the bottom of the route for belaying and then rapping to the base upon completion is recommended.

content.description:
It's sometimes worth splurging on the finer things; worth going above and beyond to treat yourself. This might mean buying a larger sized coffee than usual in the morning, getting yourself a cheeky tub of ice cream on your next grocery run, or, even, electing to buy only the choicest, most neat pickles available.

This route embodies that sort of neat pickle energy. Found up the main (north-west) face of the rock, you can expect a reachy start and a breezy finish.
content.protection: There is a sport line, but if setting top rope anchor you can use the small tree trunk as a second anchor in addition to the single hanger up top.

content.description: Keep heading left into big pockets.
